> the first return is i think needed?

@starpit Ahhh... I see it now. The trouble is that without the first `return` there is a possibility of calling `error()` followed by another call to either `error()` or `done()` in the `request` callback.

I added an `else` to my implementation in #893 (as I am personally not a fan of functions with lots of `returns`) to avoid this possibility:

``` javascript
    request(options, function(error, response, body) {
      if (error) {
        whisk.error(error);
      } else {
        console.log("Status code: " + response.statusCode);

        if(response.statusCode != 200) {
          console.log("Response from Github: " + body);
          whisk.error({response: body});
        } else {
          whisk.done({response: body});
        }
      }
    });
```
